/**
 * @page tutorial_spatial_world Tutorial: Spatial Index, Zones, and Interest Management
 *
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * A multiplayer server answers questions like "who is near the
 * player?" hundreds of times per second. Naively iterating every
 * entity is `O(N²)` and scales poorly past a few hundred actors.
 * `common_game_server` provides a **grid-based spatial index** that
 * turns these queries into cache-friendly `O(log N)` (and often
 * `O(1)`) lookups, plus a **zone system** with bitmask flags that
 * encodes PvP rules, safe zones, and area-of-effect triggers. This
 * tutorial walks through both.
 *
 * **Compilable version**: `examples/04_spatial_world.cpp`
 *
 * @section tut_spat_setup Setup
 *
 * Include the spatial-index and world headers alongside the ECS core:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "cgs/ecs/component_storage.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/ecs/entity_manager.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/game/components.hpp"       // Transform
 * #include "cgs/game/math_types.hpp"       // Vector3
 * #include "cgs/game/spatial_index.hpp"    // SpatialIndex
 * #include "cgs/game/world_components.hpp" // Zone, MapMembership, VisibilityRange
 * #include "cgs/game/world_types.hpp"      // MapType, ZoneType, ZoneFlags
 *
 * using namespace cgs::game;
 * @endcode
 *
 * Link against `cgs::game_world_system` (it pulls in the spatial index).
 *
 * @section tut_spat_index The Spatial Index
 *
 * `SpatialIndex` is a sparse uniform grid keyed on `(x, z)` world
 * coordinates. Only occupied cells exist in memory, so a 1 km²
 * world with 10,000 actors consumes roughly 10,000 × 2 hash entries,
 * not a full grid. Three operations mutate the index:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * SpatialIndex index(/* cellSize */ 32.0f);   // kDefaultCellSize
 *
 * index.Insert(entity, position);             // first placement
 * index.Update(entity, newPosition);          // after movement
 * index.Remove(entity);                       // on destroy
 * @endcode
 *
 * `Update` is smart: if the entity stays in the same cell, no hash
 * table churn happens — it only updates the stored coordinate. If
 * the entity crosses a cell boundary, the old cell's bucket is
 * rewritten and the new cell's bucket is appended to. This makes
 * the index efficient for slow-moving actors (most NPCs) and only
 * slightly more expensive for fast movers (projectiles).
 *
 * Three query methods are available:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * // All entities within a radius of a world point (exact filter).
 * std::vector<Entity> nearby = index.QueryRadius(center, 15.0f);
 *
 * // All entities in the single cell containing a world point.
 * std::vector<Entity> cellBucket = index.QueryPosition(worldPos);
 *
 * // All entities in a specific grid cell by integer coords.
 * std::vector<Entity> exact = index.QueryCell(gridX, gridY);
 * @endcode
 *
 * `QueryRadius` is the most common — it scans the cells that
 * intersect the query circle and then applies exact distance
 * filtering, so false positives from the grid rounding are removed.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_cell_size Choosing the Cell Size
 *
 * Cell size is a tuning knob, not a set-and-forget constant:
 *
 * | Cell size | Effect |
 * |---|---|
 * | **Too small** (< average visibility range / 4) | Many cells to visit per query. Hash-map overhead dominates. |
 * | **Too large** (> average visibility range × 2) | Queries return large candidate sets that must be filtered. |
 * | **Sweet spot** (≈ visibility range) | One query touches ~3×3 = 9 cells on average. Minimizes total work. |
 *
 * Default `kDefaultCellSize = 32.0f` assumes a default visibility
 * range of `kDefaultVisibilityRange = 100.0f`. If your game uses
 * different values, benchmark both extremes and pick the value that
 * minimizes per-query latency at your expected population.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_zones Zones and Flags
 *
 * A zone is a rectangular (or composite) region of a map that
 * carries gameplay rules. Zones are represented as ECS components:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * struct Zone {
 *     uint32_t zoneId = 0;
 *     ZoneType type = ZoneType::Normal;
 *     ZoneFlags flags = ZoneFlags::None;
 *     cgs::ecs::Entity mapEntity;  // the owning map instance
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * `ZoneType` is a coarse classification (`Normal`, `PvP`, `Safe`,
 * `Contested`). `ZoneFlags` is a bitmask for per-rule toggles:
 *
 * | Flag | Meaning |
 * |---|---|
 * | `NoCombat` | All damage is rejected |
 * | `NoMount` | Mounts are forcibly dismounted |
 * | `NoFly` | Flying mounts cannot take off |
 * | `Sanctuary` | Full protection (no combat, no dueling) |
 * | `Resting` | Grants rested XP bonus to players here |
 * | `FreeForAll` | Faction rules disabled, everyone is a target |
 * | `Indoor` | No weather effects, no sky rendering |
 *
 * Combine flags with bitwise OR and test with `HasFlag`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * Zone sanctuary;
 * sanctuary.zoneId = 1;
 * sanctuary.type = ZoneType::Safe;
 * sanctuary.flags = ZoneFlags::NoCombat
 *                 | ZoneFlags::Sanctuary
 *                 | ZoneFlags::Resting;
 *
 * if (HasFlag(sanctuary.flags, ZoneFlags::NoCombat)) {
 *     // Reject the damage event.
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * Combat, AI, and movement systems query their entity's current
 * zone on each tick via `WorldSystem::GetEntityZoneFlags(entity)`.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_map_membership Map Instances and Membership
 *
 * `MapInstance` tags an entity as a "map anchor" — the logical
 * owner of a spatial index:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * struct MapInstance {
 *     uint32_t mapId = 0;
 *     uint32_t instanceId = 0;  // distinguishes parallel copies
 *     MapType type = MapType::OpenWorld;
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * Every actor carries a `MapMembership` pointing at its current map
 * entity:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * struct MapMembership {
 *     cgs::ecs::Entity mapEntity;
 *     uint32_t zoneId = 0;
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * `WorldSystem` maintains a `std::unordered_map<Entity, SpatialIndex>`
 * keyed on the map entity, so multiple map instances coexist in the
 * same process without interfering.
 *
 * `TransferEntity(e, targetMap, destPos)` atomically updates the
 * Transform, swaps the MapMembership, removes from the old index,
 * and inserts into the new one:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto result = worldSystem.TransferEntity(player, dungeonMap, spawnPoint);
 * if (result != TransitionResult::Success) {
 *     // Handle InvalidMap / InvalidZone / EntityNotFound
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section tut_spat_interest Interest Management
 *
 * In a live MMO, sending every position update to every client is
 * bandwidth-prohibitive. **Interest management** only sends updates
 * about entities a given viewer can actually perceive. It is built
 * on top of the spatial index and the `VisibilityRange` component:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * struct VisibilityRange {
 *     float range = kDefaultVisibilityRange;  // 100.0f default
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * `WorldSystem::GetVisibleEntities(viewer)` returns the set of
 * entities within the viewer's visibility range AND in the same
 * map instance:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * std::vector<Entity> visible = worldSystem.GetVisibleEntities(player);
 * // Send position updates only for entities in `visible`.
 * @endcode
 *
 * For custom AI aggro ranges, query the spatial index directly
 * with a different radius:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * const auto aggroed = index.QueryRadius(npcPos, npcAggroRange);
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section tut_spat_advanced Advanced: Moving Entities Through the Index
 *
 * When an entity moves every tick, you have two choices for keeping
 * the index in sync:
 *
 * **Option A — WorldSystem synchronization (recommended)**. Attach
 * a Transform + MapMembership to every actor and let `WorldSystem`
 * synchronize the index each tick. This is the default mode; you
 * never touch `SpatialIndex` directly:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * WorldSystem worldSystem(transforms, memberships, mapInstances,
 *                         visibilityRanges, zones);
 * worldSystem.Execute(0.05f);  // syncs every tracked Transform
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Option B — Manual update**. If you have a custom movement
 * system and want to minimize extra work, call `index.Update(e, pos)`
 * yourself whenever you mutate the Transform. This bypasses the
 * WorldSystem's per-tick sync and saves redundant work, at the
 * cost of one more place where you must remember to update.
 *
 * Do NOT mix the two modes on the same entities — pick one per
 * actor class to avoid double-updates or stale cells.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_debugging Debugging Tips
 *
 * 1. **`index.Size()` must match your alive-entity count.** If it
 *    drifts, you forgot to `Remove()` destroyed entities. Put a
 *    temporary assert in your destroy pipeline.
 *
 * 2. **Print cell coordinates in logs.** Use
 *    `index.WorldToCell(pos)` to get the `CellCoord` for a
 *    position, and log it alongside player IDs when debugging
 *    "wrong bucket" issues.
 *
 * 3. **QueryRadius returning fewer entities than expected?** The
 *    index uses X and Z only — Y is ignored. If your entities are
 *    stacked vertically, they share the same cell and the same
 *    query result. Use a custom filter after the query for
 *    height-aware logic.
 *
 * 4. **Grid cell thrashing.** An entity that zigzags back and
 *    forth across a cell boundary every tick rewrites two hash
 *    buckets per tick. For such entities, consider a larger cell
 *    size or snap movement to larger deltas.
 *
 * 5. **Trace all `WorldSystem::TransferEntity` calls.** Map
 *    transitions are the most bug-prone operation — they touch
 *    Transform, MapMembership, and two different SpatialIndexes.
 *    Log every transition with player ID, from-map, to-map.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_pitfalls Common Pitfalls
 *
 * 1. **Insert without Remove.** If you skip `Remove()` in your
 *    destroy path, the index grows forever and eventually returns
 *    handles to dead entities from queries. Always Remove before
 *    or after `em.Destroy`.
 *
 * 2. **Ignoring Y.** The grid is 2D. A projectile 200 units above
 *    an actor is still in the same cell. Filter on `y` after
 *    calling `QueryRadius` if vertical separation matters for
 *    your game.
 *
 * 3. **Cell size = visibility range.** Tempting but wrong. With
 *    a cell size equal to your visibility range, queries touch
 *    a 2×2 cell window and return lots of near-duplicates. Aim
 *    for cell size ≈ query radius — not visibility range.
 *
 * 4. **Rebuilding the index every tick.** Calling `Clear` + bulk
 *    `Insert` each tick defeats the purpose of incremental
 *    updates. Always `Update` individual entities unless the
 *    whole map genuinely resets (e.g., a PvP arena round ends).
 *
 * 5. **Using one SpatialIndex across multiple maps.** Each map
 *    instance needs its own index. Mixing them creates
 *    false-positive query hits and mis-targets damage events.
 *    `WorldSystem` handles this correctly via the per-map map.
 *
 * 6. **ZoneFlags as a ZoneType.** `ZoneType` is a coarse
 *    classification (`PvP`, `Safe`, etc.). `ZoneFlags` is the
 *    bitmask of detailed rules. Don't conflate them: a zone can
 *    be `ZoneType::Normal` with `ZoneFlags::NoCombat` set.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_performance Performance Notes
 *
 * - **Insert / Update / Remove are `O(1)`** hash operations.
 *   Measured at ~50 ns per call on an M2 Mac.
 * - **QueryRadius visits ~`(2r/cellSize)²` cells** and filters
 *   each bucket exactly. For radius=100, cellSize=32 it touches
 *   ~9 cells.
 * - **Memory per tracked entity is ~48 bytes** (one
 *   `unordered_map<Entity, CellCoord>` entry plus a slot in the
 *   cell bucket). For 10,000 entities that's ~500 KB — trivial.
 * - **The grid is sparse**, so a 10 km² world with 1,000 actors
 *   uses 1,000 buckets, not `(10000/32)² = 97,656` empty slots.
 * - **Thread safety is NOT provided.** If multiple threads
 *   update the index, wrap it in a `std::shared_mutex` and take
 *   exclusive on writes.
 * - **Batch queries beat individual queries.** If you need
 *   results for 100 players in one tick, call QueryRadius 100
 *   times inside a single function so the hash tables stay in
 *   L1 cache between calls.
 * - **`Update` on a non-moved entity is ~20 ns** (short-circuits
 *   on same cell). No allocations.
 *
 * @section tut_spat_next Next Steps
 *
